  <div slot="quick-answer">
    <p><strong>Quick Answer:</strong> Good natural wine usually starts around $22 to $30, with the best value often living between $28 and $45. Below that, bottles can feel more like trend purchases than serious wine. Above that, you should expect stronger farming, more character, or real producer reputation, not just funky-label markup.</p>
  </div>

  <p>Natural wine pricing confuses people because the category mixes real artisanal costs with a lot of cultural hype. Some bottles cost more because they come from small farms, lower-intervention cellars, and tiny production runs. Others cost more because the label looks cool and the shop knows the category is fashionable. The job here is to separate the first group from the second.</p>

  <p>If you need the broader style explanation first, start in the <a href="/learn" class="internal-link">wine guide library</a>. This page is narrower: what natural wine should cost, where the value bands actually are, and which bottles make sense for real buying decisions.</p>

  <h2>Price Tiers That Actually Matter</h2>

  <p><strong>$15-22:</strong> entry-level natural wine. This tier can be fun, but it is also where flawed bottles, unstable bottlings, and hype labels show up most often. Buy here only from producers or shops you trust.</p>

  <p><strong>$22-35:</strong> the most useful value zone. You can find clean, characterful bottles from strong growers without paying scarcity pricing. This is where most drinkers should start.</p>

  <p><strong>$35-50:</strong> serious natural wine. Better sites, stronger farming, and more coherent producer identity start to show. If you already know you enjoy the category, this is usually the sweet spot.</p>

  <p><strong>$50+:</strong> prestige, rarity, or more ambitious cellar work. Spend here only when you know the producer or want a specific style. High price alone does not protect you from volatile, awkward wine.</p>

  <h2>Best Bottles By Budget</h2>
